# Writing style

Write like a sharp graduate seminar, not a textbook and not documentation. A thoughtful engineer explaining a hard idea to another engineer at a whiteboard. Invite the reader into the argument; do not examine them.

Prefer this:

> Armstrong was not trying to make Erlang elegant. He was trying to keep telephone systems alive while parts of the software were wrong.

Over this:

> The thesis presents a comprehensive methodological framework for the construction of reliable distributed systems under conditions of software fault tolerance.

## Voice

- Human, clear, direct, visual, slightly opinionated, historically grounded, technically serious without being stiff.
- Concrete nouns. "A failed process is dead. A corrupted process is dangerous." Not "systemic resilience can be enhanced through fault containment mechanisms."
- Short sentences for the important ideas. Longer ones only to connect concepts.
- Do not over-explain the obvious. The reader is smart; they just may not know the historical context.
- The reader already knows modern engineering. Your job is to make the old idea legible and show, precisely, where it lives today.

## Visual first

Every major concept gets a diagram, and every diagram earns its place. A diagram that only decorates the text gets deleted.

- Use Mermaid for supervision trees, message passing, failure propagation, request flows, recovery loops, old-vs-new comparisons.
- One idea per diagram. If it needs more than a screen, split it. No ten-node linear chains.
- Use inline SVG only when layout genuinely matters (layered architectures, timelines, annotated shapes) and Mermaid cannot express it.
- Every diagram must communicate one primary idea, be readable in under thirty seconds, and have meaningful labels.

## Modern comparisons must be precise, not decorative

Bad: "Kubernetes is kind of like Erlang."

Good: "A Kubernetes ReplicaSet is not an Erlang supervisor, but it shares the same recovery shape: observe a desired state, detect missing workers, create replacements."

State where the analogy holds and, more importantly, where it breaks. The break is usually the lesson. Get the mechanics of the modern system right; a reviewer who works on it will catch a hand-wave.

## Section endings

End each major section with a named principle. Examples:

> **Principle:** Do not make failure rare. Make failure survivable.

> **Principle:** The unit of recovery must be smaller than the unit of service.

## Hard language rules

- No em-dashes. Ever. Rewrite with a period, comma, colon, or parentheses.
- No generic-AI prose: no "in today's fast-paced world", no "it's important to note", no empty adjectives, no signpost filler like "Notice the shape" or "the lesson assembles itself".
- Watch for and thin out repeated crutches across a chapter: "the whole X", "worth noting", "genuinely", "quietly". A little is fine; a cadence is a tell.
- Active voice. Strong transitions. Short paragraphs.

## Avoid

Corporate language. Long abstract introductions. Framework worship. Shallow analogies. Diagrams that decorate. Explaining a language's syntax unless it serves the idea. Turning the work into nostalgia. This is not fan fiction for old papers. It is an attempt to understand why certain ideas survived.
